    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Otto W. Haisley (1884-1959) was born in Fairmount, Indiana. He attended Earlham College at Richmond, Indiana, the University of Michigan, the University of Wisconsin, and Columbia University. From 1913 to 1916 he taught high school in San Antonio, Texas, after which he began a long career as a school superintendent, first in Niles, Michigan (1917-1924), then in Ann Arbor, Michigan (1924-1953). In his role as superintendent, Haisley worked toward rounding out the strict academic curriculum with vocational courses. His goal was to expand the number and range of non-academic courses in order to benefit those students not intending to go to college.</p>
      <p>One of Haisley's major contributions to his profession was his formula for establishing salaries for superintendents, which was used nationwide. Haisley was active in many associations and clubs, including the Michigan Association of School Administrators, National Educational Association, Elks Club, and Rotary Club.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Otto W. Haisley collection consists of five series: Personal (1934-1960); Correspondence (1906-1958); Publications, Speeches, and Clippings (1924-1954); Superintendent's Office (1929-1954); Family Papers; and Photographs. Within each series, files are arranged alphabetically by topic.</p>
    </scopecontent>
